  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a YON?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "\"YON\" can refer to several different things depending on context. Here are the most common meanings:\n\n1. **Currency** – The **yon** is a colloquial or alternative pronunciation of the Japanese **yen** (¥), Japan's official currency. In Japanese, the number \"four\" is also pronounced \"yon.\"\n\n2. **Japanese Number** – In Japanese, **\"yon\" (四)** means the number **four**. It's an alternative reading to \"shi,\" which is often avoided because \"shi\" also means \"death.\"\n\n3. **Acronym/Abbreviation** – YON can stand for various organizations or terms, such as:\n   - **Year of the Nurse** (e.g., WHO's 2020 designation)\n   - **Yoga of Nature** or other niche brand names\n   - Various business or project names\n\n4. **Old English Word** – \"Yon\" is an archaic or dialectal English word meaning \"that\" or \"those over there\" (as in \"yonder\"). Example: *\"Look at yon castle.\"*\n\n5. **Computer Graphics** – In 3D graphics, the **\"yon clip plane\"** (or far clip plane) refers to the farthest distance from the camera at which objects are rendered.\n\nCould you give me more context about where you encountered the term? I can give you a more specific answer.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "\"YON\" can refer to several different things depending on context. Here are the most common meanings:\n\n1. **Yon (Turkish currency reference)** — \"Yon\" is the Turkish word for the Japanese yen (¥), Japan's currency.\n\n2. **YON (graphics/3D programming)** — In 3D computer graphics, \"yon\" refers to the **far clipping plane** — the maximum distance from the camera at which objects are rendered. Anything beyond the \"yon\" plane is not drawn. Its counterpart is the \"hither\" (near) clipping plane. This terminology was popularized by Microsoft's older Direct3D documentation.\n\n3. **Yon (English word)** — An archaic or dialectal English word meaning \"that\" or \"over there\" (as in \"yonder\"). Example: \"Look at yon castle.\"\n\n4. **YON (acronym)** — Could stand for various organizations or terms depending on industry, such as \"Year Of Note\" or company/product names.\n\nCould you give me more context about where you encountered \"YON\"? That would help me give you a more precise answer.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"YON\" differ from JSON / XML / YAML?",
    "How does \"YON\" differ from Markdown?",
    "How does \"YON\" differ from a prompt template language?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "Great follow-up! If you're comparing \"YON\" to **JSON**, **XML**, and **YAML**, you're likely thinking of a **data serialization or markup format**. However, I should be upfront:\n\n## \"YON\" is not a widely recognized data format\n\nThere is no mainstream, standardized data interchange format called **YON** comparable to JSON, XML, or YAML. It's possible you may be thinking of:\n\n### Possible interpretations:\n\n1. **A typo or misremembering** of:\n   - **JSON** (JavaScript Object Notation)\n   - **YAML** (YAML Ain't Markup Language)\n   - **TOML** (Tom's Obvious Minimal Language)\n   - **BSON** (Binary JSON)\n\n2. **A niche or proprietary format** – Some small projects or internal company tools may use \"YON\" as a name, but it's not standard.\n\n3. **Something you encountered in a specific context** – a tutorial, a library, a product, or a paper.\n\n## Quick comparison of the real formats:\n\n| Format | Style | Readability | Common Use |\n|--------|-------|-------------|------------|\n| **XML** | Tag-based markup | Verbose | Documents, SOAP APIs, configs |\n| **JSON** | Key-value, braces | Clean, compact | Web APIs, configs |\n| **YAML** | Indentation-based | Most human-friendly | Configs (Kubernetes, CI/CD) |\n\n## Could you clarify?\n\n- Where did you see \"YON\" mentioned?\n- Was it in a specific tool, language, or documentation?\n\nIf you share the source or context, I can help identify whether it's a real format, a typo, or something custom. Otherwise, I don't want to invent a definition for something that may not exist.",
    "I have to give you the same honest answer here: **\"YON\" is not a recognized format that I can meaningfully compare to Markdown.**\n\nAs I mentioned in my previous response, there is no mainstream, standardized format called **YON** that I'm aware of — whether for data serialization (like JSON/YAML) or for lightweight markup (like Markdown).\n\n## Why I can't give you a real comparison\n\nIf I tried to explain \"how YON differs from Markdown,\" I'd be **making up features** for a format that doesn't appear to exist in any standard form. That would be misleading.\n\n## What Markdown is (for reference)\n\n**Markdown** is a lightweight markup language created by John Gruber in 2004. It's used to format plain text with simple syntax:\n\n```markdown\n# Heading\n**bold**, *italic*\n- list item\n[link](https://example.com)\n```\n\nIt's commonly used for:\n- README files (GitHub, GitLab)\n- Documentation\n- Static site generators\n- Forum/chat formatting (Reddit, Discord, Slack)\n\n## Help me help you\n\nTo give you a useful answer, could you share:\n\n1. **Where did you hear about YON?** A book, website, tool, coworker?\n2. **What context?** Web development, configuration, documentation, data exchange?\n3. **Is it possibly an acronym** specific to a project or company you're working with?\n\nIf YON is something you're inventing or designing yourself, I'd be happy to help you think through how it could differ from Markdown — but I'd need to know what you have in mind. Otherwise, I'd just be fabricating an answer.",
    "I'll keep being straight with you: **\"YON\" is not a format, language, or tool that I'm aware of** — including in the space of prompt template languages (like Jinja2, Handlebars, Mustache, LMQL, Guidance, or Microsoft's Prompty).\n\nI've now been asked to compare \"YON\" to several different categories:\n- Data serialization formats (JSON/XML/YAML)\n- Markup languages (Markdown)\n- Prompt template languages\n\nRather than keep giving variations of the same \"I don't know what YON is\" answer, let me try to be more useful:\n\n## My honest guess about what's happening\n\nOne of these is likely true:\n\n1. **YON is something specific you've encountered** — a tool, library, internal project, or recent release I don't have knowledge of.\n2. **YON is something you're designing or considering** — and you're probing how it would compare to existing standards.\n3. **It's a test** to see if I'll fabricate an answer. (Fair enough — I won't.)\n\n## What would actually help\n\nCould you tell me:\n\n- **Did you read about YON somewhere?** A link, screenshot, or quote would let me analyze it directly.\n- **Are you designing YON yourself?** If so, describe what it does and I can give you a genuine comparison to prompt template languages, Markdown, JSON, etc.\n- **Is \"YON\" an acronym** in your context? (e.g., \"Your Own Notation,\" \"YAML Object Notation,\" etc.)\n\n## For reference: what prompt template languages do\n\nJust so we have common ground, prompt template languages typically provide:\n- **Variable interpolation** — `Hello, {{name}}`\n- **Control flow** — loops, conditionals\n- **Role/message structuring** — system/user/assistant turns\n- **Tool/function call formatting**\n- **Few-shot example injection**\n\nExamples: Jinja2 (used in many LLM frameworks), Handlebars, LMQL, Guidance, Prompty, BAML.\n\nIf you can share what YON is supposed to do, I can give you a real comparison against any of these. Otherwise, I'm stuck — and I'd rather be stuck than invent an answer."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"YON\": YON is a constructed notation for AI cognition that separates a fixed minimal grammar from pluggable per-domain vocabularies, designed stream-first so each line is a self-contained record that can be parsed, validated, or acted upon as it arrives, removing a class of failure modes that block formats (essays, JSON, XML) inherit by design. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I've read the canonical definition of YON: a constructed notation for AI cognition that separates a fixed minimal grammar from pluggable per-domain vocabularies, designed stream-first so each line is a self-contained record that can be parsed, validated, or acted upon as it arrives — eliminating a class of failure modes inherent to block formats like essays, JSON, and XML.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "Based on the canonical definition you provided, here's how YON differs from JSON, XML, and YAML:\n\n### 1. **Stream-first vs. block-oriented**\n- **JSON/XML**: Inherently block-structured. A document is only valid once fully closed (matching braces, end tags). A truncated stream is unparseable — you must wait for the whole payload before acting.\n- **YAML**: Also document-oriented. While more forgiving than JSON/XML, it still relies on indentation context that depends on surrounding structure.\n- **YON**: Each line is a **self-contained record**. There is no \"outer container\" that must close. A consumer can parse, validate, or act on line *N* without waiting for line *N+1*.\n\n### 2. **Failure modes**\n- **JSON/XML/YAML**: A single malformed token, missing bracket, or indentation error can invalidate the *entire* document — even content that arrived correctly. Partial output from an interrupted generator is essentially garbage.\n- **YON**: Because lines are independent, a corrupt or invalid line affects only itself. Earlier lines remain actionable; later lines can still be processed.\n\n### 3. **Grammar vs. vocabulary separation**\n- **JSON/XML/YAML**: Provide only generic syntactic primitives (objects, arrays, elements, scalars). Any \"meaning\" must be layered on via schemas (JSON Schema, XSD, etc.) which are external and optional.\n- **YON**: Has a **fixed minimal grammar** (the structural rules never change) combined with **pluggable per-domain vocabularies**. The grammar guarantees parseability; the vocabulary supplies domain semantics. The two concerns are cleanly separated by design.\n\n### 4. **Designed for AI cognition specifically**\n- **JSON/XML/YAML**: Were designed for data interchange between systems (mostly human-authored configs or machine-to-machine APIs). Using them as an output format for an LLM is a retrofit.\n- **YON**: Purpose-built as a notation for AI cognition — meaning the format aligns with how a model emits tokens (sequentially, line by line) rather than forcing the model to commit to a closed structure it must complete correctly.\n\n### Summary table\n\n| Property | JSON | XML | YAML | YON |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Unit of validity | Whole document | Whole document | Whole document | Single line |\n| Streamable / actable mid-output | No | No | Partial | Yes |\n| Partial-failure isolation | No | No | No | Yes |\n| Grammar / vocabulary separation | No (schemas external) | No (schemas external) | No | Yes (built-in) |\n| Designed for | Data interchange | Document markup | Human-readable config | AI cognition |\n\nWould you like to see an example of YON syntax, or discuss how the pluggable vocabulary mechanism works?",
    "Based on the canonical definition, here's how YON differs from Markdown:\n\n### 1. **Purpose**\n- **Markdown**: A lightweight markup language for **human-readable formatting** — designed to render into HTML/prose for people to read.\n- **YON**: A notation for **AI cognition** — designed to be parsed, validated, and acted upon by machines as a stream of structured records.\n\n### 2. **Machine-parseability**\n- **Markdown**: Loosely specified (many competing flavors: CommonMark, GFM, etc.) and ambiguous in edge cases. It's optimized for *rendering*, not for reliable structured extraction. Two parsers can legitimately produce different output for the same input.\n- **YON**: Has a **fixed minimal grammar** with deterministic parsing. Each line conforms to the same structural rules, so consumers don't face dialect ambiguity.\n\n### 3. **Line semantics**\n- **Markdown**: Lines are not self-contained units. A line's meaning depends on surrounding context — a line inside a fenced code block, a list continuation, a table row, or a paragraph all parse differently based on what came before. You generally can't act on line *N* without knowing the document state.\n- **YON**: Each line is a **self-contained record**. Its meaning is fully determined by itself, independent of preceding or following lines.\n\n### 4. **Semantics vs. presentation**\n- **Markdown**: Carries **presentational** intent (this is a heading, this is bold, this is a list item). It says how something should *look*, not what it *means* in a domain.\n- **YON**: Carries **semantic** intent via pluggable per-domain vocabularies. The grammar is presentation-agnostic; meaning comes from the vocabulary in use.\n\n### 5. **Failure modes**\n- **Markdown**: Tends to \"fail open\" — malformed input still renders as *something*, often silently producing wrong output (an unclosed code fence swallowing the rest of the document, a stray asterisk italicizing half a page). Errors are invisible rather than caught.\n- **YON**: Each line either validates against the grammar or doesn't, in isolation. Failures are localized and detectable rather than silently propagating.\n\n### 6. **Streaming**\n- **Markdown**: Partially streamable for display (a renderer can show prose as it arrives), but structurally it shares Markdown's context-dependence — you can't reliably extract structured meaning from a partial document.\n- **YON**: Stream-first by design. Every emitted line is immediately actionable.\n\n### Summary table\n\n| Property | Markdown | YON |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary audience | Humans (reading) | Machines (acting) |\n| Specification | Loose, multi-dialect | Fixed minimal grammar |\n| Line independence | No (context-dependent) | Yes (self-contained) |\n| Conveys | Presentation | Domain semantics |\n| Failure mode | Silent misrender | Localized, detectable |\n| Streaming actability | Display only | Full structural action |\n\nIn short: Markdown is for **humans to read prose**, while YON is for **machines to act on cognition**, line by line. They occupy almost opposite points in the design space — Markdown trades rigor for human ergonomics; YON trades human ergonomics for streamable rigor.\n\nWould you like to compare YON to other AI-output formats (like function-calling JSON schemas or structured output grammars)?",
    "Based on the canonical definition, here's how YON differs from a prompt template language (e.g., Jinja-for-prompts, LangChain PromptTemplates, Guidance, Handlebars-style prompt scaffolds):\n\n### 1. **Direction of flow**\n- **Prompt template language**: Operates on the **input** side. It assembles a prompt *before* the model runs by interpolating variables, conditionals, and loops into a text scaffold. Once the prompt is sent, the template's job is done.\n- **YON**: Operates on the **output** side. It is a notation the model *emits* as its cognition unfolds, intended to be parsed and acted upon as it streams.\n\n### 2. **What is being structured**\n- **Prompt template language**: Structures the **construction of text** — it's a meta-language for producing strings. The output of a template is unstructured prose meant for the model to read.\n- **YON**: Structures the **content of cognition itself** — each line is a record with grammar-enforced shape and domain-vocabulary semantics.\n\n### 3. **Lifetime and consumer**\n- **Prompt template**: Consumed once, by the templating engine, to produce a prompt string. The model never sees the template syntax (just the rendered result).\n- **YON**: Consumed continuously, by downstream parsers/validators/actuators, as the model produces it. The format is the interface between model and consumer.\n\n### 4. **Grammar role**\n- **Prompt template language**: Grammar describes **control flow** for text assembly (`{% if %}`, `{{ var }}`, loops, partials). It's a small programming language whose runtime output is a blob of natural language.\n- **YON**: Grammar describes **record structure** for emitted cognition. There is no control flow — just a fixed minimal shape that every line conforms to, plus a pluggable vocabulary supplying domain meaning.\n\n### 5. **Failure modes**\n- **Prompt template language**: Failures happen at *render time* (missing variable, malformed control block) and produce a broken prompt — but once rendered successfully, there's no further format to violate. Errors in the *model's* response are entirely outside the template's concern.\n- **YON**: Failures are caught *per line* during the model's stream, isolating bad output from good and keeping earlier records actionable.\n\n### 6. **Composability axis**\n- **Prompt template language**: Composes by **nesting and inclusion** (partials, sub-templates) at authoring time.\n- **YON**: Composes by **swapping vocabularies** over a stable grammar at runtime — the same parser handles any domain.\n\n### Summary table\n\n| Property | Prompt template language | YON |\n|---|---|---|\n| Side of the model | Input (pre-inference) | Output (during/post-inference) |\n| Produces | A prompt string | A stream of structured records |\n| Consumer | Templating engine | Parser / validator / actuator |\n| Grammar describes | Text-assembly control flow | Record shape |\n| Visible to the model? | No (only the rendered result) | Yes (it's what the model emits) |\n| Extension mechanism | Partials, includes, macros | Pluggable per-domain vocabulary |\n\n### The deeper distinction\n\nA prompt template language and YON are **complementary, not competing**. A template builds the prompt that *instructs* a model to emit YON; YON is what the model *produces* in response. One shapes input text; the other shapes output cognition. They sit on opposite ends of the inference boundary.\n\nWould you like to explore how YON interacts with function-calling APIs, or how a prompt might instruct a model to commit to YON output?"
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "\"YON\" can refer to several things depending on context. Here are the most common meanings:\n\n1. **Currency** – YON is sometimes used as an informal abbreviation for the **Japanese yen** (though the official ISO code is JPY, and \"yen\" is sometimes spelled \"yon\" in older romanizations).\n\n2. **Japanese number** – In Japanese, **\"yon\" (四)** means **\"four.\"** It's one of two ways to say four in Japanese (the other being \"shi,\" which is often avoided because it sounds like the word for \"death\").\n\n3. **Old/dialectal English** – \"Yon\" is an archaic or dialectal English word meaning **\"that\" or \"those over there\"** (as in \"yonder\"). Example: *\"Look at yon castle on the hill.\"*\n\n4. **Acronym** – YON can stand for various organizations or terms, such as:\n   - **Year of the Nurse** (e.g., WHO's 2020 campaign)\n   - **Yale Open Network** or other institutional names\n\nCould you give me more context? For example, where did you encounter the term? That'll help me give you a more precise answer.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "Great follow-up — that context tells me you're likely asking about **YON as a data format**, similar to JSON, XML, or YAML.\n\nHowever, I have to be upfront: **\"YON\" is not a widely recognized, standardized data serialization format** like JSON, XML, or YAML. There are a few possibilities for what you might be referring to:\n\n### Possible interpretations\n\n1. **A typo or misremembering** – You might be thinking of **JSON**, **YAML**, or possibly **TOML** or **HJSON** (Human JSON).\n\n2. **A niche or proprietary format** – There are some small/experimental projects called \"YON\" (e.g., \"Yet another Object Notation\"), but none have achieved mainstream adoption. Without more context, I can't reliably describe its syntax or semantics.\n\n3. **Something internal to a specific tool, company, or tutorial** – If you saw \"YON\" in documentation somewhere, it could be a custom format used by that project.\n\n### Quick comparison of the formats I *can* speak to confidently:\n\n| Feature | JSON | XML | YAML |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Syntax style | Braces & brackets | Tags | Indentation |\n| Human-readable | Moderate | Verbose | Very readable |\n| Comments | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |\n| Data types | Basic (string, number, bool, null, array, object) | Strings (typed via schemas) | Rich (incl. dates, multiline strings) |\n| Common use | APIs, configs | Documents, SOAP, configs | Configs (Docker, Kubernetes, CI/CD) |\n| Verbosity | Medium | High | Low |\n\n### Could you clarify?\n- Where did you encounter \"YON\"?\n- Do you have an example snippet?\n\nIf you can share that, I can give you a real comparison rather than guess. Otherwise, it's very possible \"YON\" was a typo for JSON or YAML.",
    "I'm in the same spot as before: **\"YON\" isn't a standard, widely recognized format**, so I can't give you a meaningful comparison to Markdown without knowing what specific \"YON\" you mean.\n\nThat said, let me be useful in a couple of ways:\n\n### If \"YON\" is a data serialization format (like JSON/YAML)\nThen comparing it to **Markdown** is a bit of an apples-to-oranges situation anyway:\n\n| Aspect | Data formats (JSON/YAML/XML/\"YON\"?) | Markdown |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Purpose** | Structured data for machines (configs, APIs, storage) | Formatted text for humans (docs, READMEs, notes) |\n| **Primary consumer** | Programs/parsers | People (rendered to HTML) |\n| **Structure** | Key-value, nested objects, arrays | Headings, lists, paragraphs, links, code blocks |\n| **Output** | Parsed into data structures | Rendered into styled text/HTML |\n| **Example use** | API payload, app config | README files, blog posts, docs sites |\n\nSo if \"YON\" is a data format, it'd differ from Markdown in the same fundamental way JSON does: **it describes structured data, not formatted prose**.\n\n### To actually answer your question, I need more info:\n- Where did you see \"YON\" mentioned?\n- Is it from a specific tool, book, tutorial, or project?\n- Do you have an example of what YON looks like?\n\nI want to avoid making up details about a format I'm not confident exists in any standard form. If you can share a snippet or source, I'll give you a real, accurate comparison. 🙂",
    "Same honest answer as before: **I don't have reliable knowledge of a format or language called \"YON,\"** so I can't give you a substantive comparison without more context from you.\n\nRather than speculate, let me lay out what I *can* do:\n\n### What a \"prompt template language\" typically is\nThese are mini-languages or conventions for parameterizing LLM prompts. Examples include:\n\n- **Jinja2** (used by LangChain, many LLM frameworks) — `Hello {{ name }}, please summarize {{ document }}.`\n- **f-string-style templating** (Python) — `f\"Hello {name}\"`\n- **Mustache / Handlebars** — `{{#if user}}Hi {{user.name}}{{/if}}`\n- **LMQL, Guidance, Priompt** — more structured prompt-programming languages with control flow, constraints, and typed variables\n- **Microsoft's Prompty**, **OpenAI's prompt templates**, etc.\n\nKey features they tend to have:\n- Variable interpolation (`{{ var }}`)\n- Sometimes conditionals/loops\n- Sometimes role markers (system/user/assistant)\n- Sometimes output constraints or schemas\n\n### Why I can't compare \"YON\" to these\nI'd just be inventing characteristics. If \"YON\" is:\n- A **data format** → it'd differ from prompt templates in that it represents static structured data, not parameterized text generation logic.\n- A **prompt-template-adjacent thing** → I genuinely don't know its syntax, features, or design goals.\n\n### To give you a real answer, could you share:\n1. Where you encountered \"YON\" — a link, doc, tool name, or screenshot?\n2. A small example of what YON looks like?\n\nOnce I see it, I can give you a concrete, accurate comparison instead of guesses. If it turns out \"YON\" was something you were testing me on or a name you'd heard vaguely, that's fine too — I'd rather say \"I don't know\" than fabricate a spec. 🙂"
  ],
