        "assistant": "Based on the canonical definition you provided, here's how YON differs from JSON, XML, and YAML:\n\n### 1. **Stream-first vs. block-oriented**\n- **JSON/XML**: Inherently block-structured. A document is only valid once fully closed (matching braces, end tags). A truncated stream is unparseable — you must wait for the whole payload before acting.\n- **YAML**: Also document-oriented. While more forgiving than JSON/XML, it still relies on indentation context that depends on surrounding structure.\n- **YON**: Each line is a **self-contained record**. There is no \"outer container\" that must close. A consumer can parse, validate, or act on line *N* without waiting for line *N+1*.\n\n### 2. **Failure modes**\n- **JSON/XML/YAML**: A single malformed token, missing bracket, or indentation error can invalidate the *entire* document — even content that arrived correctly. Partial output from an interrupted generator is essentially garbage.\n- **YON**: Because lines are independent, a corrupt or invalid line affects only itself. Earlier lines remain actionable; later lines can still be processed.\n\n### 3. **Grammar vs. vocabulary separation**\n- **JSON/XML/YAML**: Provide only generic syntactic primitives (objects, arrays, elements, scalars). Any \"meaning\" must be layered on via schemas (JSON Schema, XSD, etc.) which are external and optional.\n- **YON**: Has a **fixed minimal grammar** (the structural rules never change) combined with **pluggable per-domain vocabularies**. The grammar guarantees parseability; the vocabulary supplies domain semantics. The two concerns are cleanly separated by design.\n\n### 4. **Designed for AI cognition specifically**\n- **JSON/XML/YAML**: Were designed for data interchange between systems (mostly human-authored configs or machine-to-machine APIs). Using them as an output format for an LLM is a retrofit.\n- **YON**: Purpose-built as a notation for AI cognition — meaning the format aligns with how a model emits tokens (sequentially, line by line) rather than forcing the model to commit to a closed structure it must complete correctly.\n\n### Summary table\n\n| Property | JSON | XML | YAML | YON |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Unit of validity | Whole document | Whole document | Whole document | Single line |\n| Streamable / actable mid-output | No | No | Partial | Yes |\n| Partial-failure isolation | No | No | No | Yes |\n| Grammar / vocabulary separation | No (schemas external) | No (schemas external) | No | Yes (built-in) |\n| Designed for | Data interchange | Document markup | Human-readable config | AI cognition |\n\nWould you like to see an example of YON syntax, or discuss how the pluggable vocabulary mechanism works?",
